<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-496-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 496 290.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  August 7 1989 v6 n31 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>McDonnell Douglas to sell Tymnet unit, field service division.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kovsky, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   McDonnell Douglas Corp. (divestment).andO;Ticker:    MD.andO;Topic:     Information SystemsDivestmentOrganization StructureAerospace IndustrySpinoffsSubsidiary CompaniesComputer Systems Integrators.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>McDonnell Douglas To Sell Tymnet Unit, Field Service DivisionandM;ST.andP;  LOUIS -- McDonnell Douglas will sell two of its information systemsbusinesses and spin off a third unit, Information Systems International, intoa public company with headquarters in the United Kingdom.andM;According to McDonnell Douglas Chairman and Chief Executive Officer JohnMcDonnel, shedding the information services is part of a move to focus on thecompany's systems integration business, based in St. Louis.andM;In addition, the proceeds of the ales will assist in reducing McDonnellDouglas' debt and increasing the resources available to the company's coreaerospace business, according to company officials.andM;Awaiting Regulatory ApprovalandM;One of the business units to be sold, the Network Systems division, includesthe Tymnet public data network.andP;  British Telecom has agreed to pay $355million for the unit, should the sale clear all required regulatoryapprovals.andM;The second unit being sold is McDonnell Douglas' North American field servicebusiness.andP;  The sale is expected to take place later this year, according tothe officials.andM;Along with McDonnell Douglas' Telecheck business, for which a sales agreementwas announced in June, the combined revenues of the three informationservices units add up to about $400 million annually, the officials said.andM;The current president of McDonnell Douglas Information Systems Co., JeremyCausley, has been appointed chief executive of the restructured InformationSystems International unit.andP;  Causley will oversee partial divestiture of thecompany, which will include McDonnell Douglas' existing U.S.-based computersystems business.andM;The current annual revenues of the businesses that will be combined under thenew United Kingdom venture total about $400 million, according to theofficials.andM;The officials declined to estimate how many positions will be eliminated as aresult of the changes.andM;The San Jose, Calif.-based Network Systems unit employs about 1,500 people.andO;The unit offers such services as Tymnet, OnTyme electronic mail, credit cardprocessing and electronic data interchange.andO;</TEXT></DOC>